A: The issue is with this line:
names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));

You're calling it.next() in the loop, which means you're always getting the next element from the same iterator. You should be getting the next element from the iterator that you created in the loop.
Try this:
for(Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot.getChildren().iterator(); it.hasNext(); ){
  i = i + 1;
  names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));
}

This way, you're getting the next element from a new iterator for each child in your dataSnapshot.

A: You are using the same iterator for all children. You should create a new iterator for each child.
Here is the correct code:
for (DataSnapshot dataSnapshot1:dataSnapshot.getChildren()) {
    Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot1.getChildren().iterator();
    while(it.hasNext()) {
        names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));
    }
}

This code will iterate over each child of dataSnapshot and then iterate over each child of those children. It will add the value of each child to the names list.

